explanation:
To determine whether OS_initfs uses any compiler language extensions you must inspect the declarations/definitions of all non-plain-C tokens and any symbols that could hide extensions via attributes/macros: 

- OS_FileSys_Initialize: its prototype may include compiler-specific attributes (e.g. __attribute__((...))), nonstandard calling conventions, or parameter types that themselves are extensions. You must see the declaration/definition to rule those out.

- int32: this is a typedef (not a standard C type). The underlying definition may be a standard typedef (e.g. int32_t) or a compiler-specific extension; inspect to verify.

- osal_blockcount_t: a project typedef that could be an alias to an extended type (128-bit, compiler-specific integer, or custom struct); its definition is needed to ensure no extensions are used.

- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE, OS_ERR_NO_FREE_IDS, OS_FS_ERR_DEVICE_NOT_FREE: these constants/macros could be implemented via nonstandard constructs (complex macro expressions, use of GNU extension tokens, or attributes). Their definitions are needed to ensure they are plain constants/enums.

- false: the token false may come from <stdbool.h> (standard C99) or be a custom macro/enum/extension. Confirm its origin/definition to ensure no nonstandard language feature is being relied on.

- size_t: although standard, confirm its typedef (from <stddef.h> or compiler headers) so that it is not redefined to a nonstandard/extended type in this environment.

Collecting these symbols lets the analyzer detect any use of compiler-specific attributes, nonstandard typedefs, macros that expand to extension constructs, or other language extensions that would violate the MISRA rule.
